Most important missing pieces
Paths are lost (only ancestor closure retained).
Descendant counts are discarded after IC computation.
No expansion/jump analysis is performed.
Ancestors must already be in topic members (closure & members) which excludes most useful topic labels.
Multiple inheritance paths are collapsed into a set, preventing multiple topics per CUI.
IC selects the most specific ancestor, which is almost the opposite of your new "expansion point" heuristic.

Those six items are the biggest gaps between the current implementation and the retrieval-topic approach you've been describing.
